passages.text: Flagship launch to drive seasonal pickup; limited content growth

During the earnings briefing, management guided for improved RF testing utilization ahead of the iPhone 17 launch. While RF content growth is minimal, longer test durations, potential tariff exemptions, and eSIM adoption could support volumes, driving an expected \(6\%\) FY26E RF growth. Memory segment ramp faces delays due to customer component shortages, though the optoelectronics segment is experiencing strong growth from 800G transceivers, with FY26 revenue forecast to rise \(35\%\) Y/Y. Separately, Inari and San'an acquisition of Lumileds may be able to scale INARI's revenue but at dilutive margins. Investors remain concerned about integration challenges given Lumileds' weak financials. We lower our FY26/27E forecast and extend our PT period to Jun- 26 with a higher price target of RM2.20, based on \(27x\) 12M fwd EPS (at 5- year mean). Stay Neutral.

Seasonal uptick in Sep/Dec- Q for iPhone 17 ramp but unlikely to be a game changer. Coming off a seasonally weak June quarter (4QFY25), management guided for an uptick in RF testing utilization as its key customer ramps for the iPhone 17 launch. While RF content growth remains limited, management highlighted slightly longer test durations requested by the customer due to minor design tweaks. On the positive side, we think shipment volumes could be supported by (i) potential tariff exemptions given Apple's sizable US investments, and (ii) the expected removal of the eSIM ban in China, which would benefit demand for the iPhone Slim, as the model only supports eSIM. We factor in \(6\%\) growth for the RF segment in FY26E (USD terms), underpinned by stronger- than- expected shipments in the Sep/Dec qtrs. (link).

Memory segment faces delayed ramp, but optical transceivers on the rise. The memory segment remained weak, running at a c.30- 40% utilization rate with little improvement in 4QFY25. Management attributed the delay to component shortages on the customer side, despite the group already being qualified for high- volume production (estimated RM100mn revenue/year). This could push back the ramp originally scheduled for 1QFY26. On a brighter note, the optoelectronics segment delivered meaningful growth in 4QFY25, supported by progress in the optical transceiver business. The Philippines plant (CK2.1) saw growing demand for 800G module production as more data centers migrated from lower- end modules. Additionally, Malaysian production is expected to double in 1QFY26. We forecast \(35\%\) Y/Y growth for the optoelectronics segment in FY26.

Joint acquisition of Lumileds with San'an. Management views the deal as aligned with its 'in- sourcing' strategy, similar to its anchor relationship with its RF customer. While Lumileds' 2024 revenue of US \(550mn (with c.60 - 70\%)\) COGS) suggests a meaningful top- line contribution, margins from the LED packaging business are likely dilutive to group margins, in our view. Furthermore, Lumileds' current financials (FY24 net loss: US \(67mn) represent a challenge that Inari will need to absorb in the early stages.

We are Neutral on INRI amid high 5G iPhone penetration and because we see the current 1- yr forward P/E as fair in relation to its three- year CAGR of \(7\%\) over FY24- 27E, as well as its position as a tech beta proxy given that it's the largest and most liquid tech stock in Malaysia. INRI is a key OSAT partner to Broadcom's RF filter business, which in turn supplies Apple/Samsung for their leading smartphones. Limited RF dollar content growth in subsequent iPhone launches, coupled with tepid iPhone shipment volume growth offer limited reasons to buy INRI, in our view.
Our Jun- 26 PT of RM2.20 is derived by pegging the target P/E of 27x to 12M forward EPS (in line with its 5- year mean).
